Test Document for RAG Ingestion
Title: Network Reliability Playbook – Edge Infrastructure Automation
Doc ID suggestion: edge-rel-playbook-v1
1. Overview
The Edge Infrastructure Automation System (EIAS) is responsible for provisioning, monitoring, and validating network devices across 42 global data centers. The primary objective of the system is to reduce manual configuration drift and eliminate operational toil.
The system follows a software-first approach:
All device configurations are declared in Git.
Changes are validated through preflight checks.
Provisioning occurs via automated pipelines.
Telemetry is continuously collected and evaluated.
The design philosophy is “automate everything, validate twice.”
2. Architecture
The system consists of five core services:
Config Registry
Preflight Validator
Provisioning Engine
Telemetry Collector
Alert & Remediation Service
Each service communicates via internal REST APIs.
All services are containerized and deployed using Kubernetes.
Infrastructure provisioning is managed through Terraform.
3. Config Registry
The Config Registry stores desired-state configurations for:
Core routers
Edge switches
Firewall appliances
Load balancers
Configurations are written in YAML and validated against JSON schemas.
Every configuration change requires:
Schema validation
Policy validation
Dry-run simulation
Approval workflow
Config versions are immutable. Rollbacks are implemented by redeploying a prior commit hash.
4. Preflight Validator
The Preflight Validator runs automated safety checks before any change is applied.
Checks include:
Device reachability (SSH or API)
OS version compatibility
Available memory and CPU
NTP synchronization
Required access credentials
If any check fails, provisioning is aborted.
The system enforces a “fail-fast” model — no partial execution is allowed during preflight failure.
5. Provisioning Engine
The Provisioning Engine executes configuration changes.
Key properties:
Idempotent execution
Retry with exponential backoff
Transactional grouping of related devices
Structured logging
If provisioning fails mid-execution:
The system attempts automated rollback.
If rollback fails, incident response is triggered.
Provisioning actions are tracked in an audit log database.
6. Telemetry Collector
Telemetry data includes:
Latency (ms)
Packet loss (%)
CPU utilization (%)
Memory usage (%)
Interface error rates
Telemetry is scraped every 15 seconds.
Metrics are stored in a time-series database.
Prometheus is used for scraping and rule evaluation.
Grafana is used for dashboards.
7. Alert & Remediation Service
Alerts are triggered when:
Latency exceeds 120ms for 3 consecutive intervals
Packet loss exceeds 2%
CPU exceeds 85% for 5 minutes
Alerts include:
Severity level
Affected devices
Recent configuration changes
Recommended remediation steps
For known failure patterns, automated remediation can:
Restart services
Roll back config
Shift traffic to redundant paths
8. Security Model
The system enforces:
Role-based access control (RBAC)
Short-lived credentials
Encrypted secrets storage
Audit logging of all API calls
Secrets are never stored in plaintext in Git.
Terraform state files are encrypted at rest.
9. Failure Scenarios
Scenario A – Partial Device Failure
If one device in a transactional group fails provisioning:
Remaining devices are paused.
System attempts rollback.
Incident ticket is created automatically.
Scenario B – Telemetry Spike After Deployment
If latency spikes within 10 minutes of a deployment:
The deployment is flagged as suspect.
Change metadata is attached to the alert.
Automated rollback is considered.
Scenario C – Drift Detection
If running configuration differs from declared configuration:
Drift event is logged.
Remediation playbook is executed.
Manual approval may be required depending on severity.
10. Observability Principles
The system tracks:
Deployment success rate
Mean time to detect (MTTD)
Mean time to recovery (MTTR)
Change failure rate
Structured logs include:
Correlation IDs
Device identifiers
Execution stage
Duration metrics
All services expose a /health endpoint.